We should probably have configuration for some of this. We could have a config option `auto_update_manifests`. The default could be unconfigured. When the launcher is started with a manifest with an outdated Julia version, it could show a prompt `The Julia version in this project is outdated, do you want update it (u), run with the old version (n), or always update Julia versions in this case (a), never update Julia versions in this case (x)?`

In all of these cases we'll have to do a lot of checking, though, or probably will even have to run the resolver. At the end of the day, any of the packages listed in the manifest might actually exclude the newer Julia version via a compat section in its `Project.toml`, and we'll have to respect that. I think that is one of the main reasons that in my mind we should only ever run with a different Julia version if the package manager logic has signed off on that combination. But checking all these compats is not really something we can do on the hot-path of the launcher... 

>  I think juliaup should auto-install and GC them after some number of days of not being used, leaving manually added channels alone

